‚óŹ All 18 tests pass, clippy is clean with zero warnings.

  Root cause: The worker was fabricating its own OpHandle values (starting at 0
  per worker) and storing them in a HashMap. But the actor assigns handles from
  a single global counter shared across all clients. With thread 0 getting actor
   handles 1-32 and thread 1 getting 33-64, thread 1's completions never matched
   its local handles 0-31 ‚ÄĒ so all completions were silently discarded and the
  in-flight map stayed permanently full.

  Fix: Replaced HashMap<OpHandle, (Instant, bool)> with VecDeque<(Instant, 
  bool)>. The worker no longer tries to correlate by handle at all. Since
  completions arrive in submission order on the per-client SPSC channel, we just
   push on submit and pop from the front on completion. This works correctly
  regardless of what handle values the actor assigns.

